The word "Yoga" is etymologically related to the English "yoke" (Latin: "jungere"), thus one ought to conclude the only form of Yoga valid for a Westerner today is Alphadestiny's "Yoke Workout" of cheat rows, power shrugs, rack pulls above the knee, neck curls, farmer walks, etc.

"Jungere" as "to join", to "bring together", "gather", "harness", etc. reminds me of death as "gathering one to his fathers", where innagrave the mystery of one's ancestry is revealed sepulchrally. "The secret of our paternity lies in their grave, and we must there to learn it."
Perhaps related is Gene Wolfe's story "The Seraph from Its Sepulcher", where a living man is seen as a larva of an entombed angel talking to him only in the small hours of the night
